05256nam a22007815i 9781501715587DE-B159720180924034856.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180924s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017155877 a10.7591/97815017155872doi  a(DE-B1597)496555  a(OCoLC)1013988565  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aBUS0680002bisacsh 7aHIS0320002bisacsh 7aHIS0500002bisacsh04a958.608/52231 aKalinovsky, Artemy M., eauthor.10aLaboratory of Socialist Development :bCold War Politics and Decolonization in Soviet Tajikistan /cArtemy M. Kalinovsky. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource :b16 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tMap -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tTransliteration -- tIntroduction: THE PROMISE OF DEVELOPMENT -- t1. DECOLONIZATION, DE-STALINIZATION, AND DEVELOPMENT -- t2. AYNI'S CHILDREN, OR MAKING A TAJIK-SOVIET INTELLIGENTSIA -- t3. DEFINING DEVELOPMENT -- t4. PLANS, GIFTS, AND OBLIGATIONS -- t5. NUREK, "A CITY YOU CAN WRITE ABOUT" -- t6. SHEPHERDS INTO BUILDERS -- t7. THE COUNTRYSIDE ELECTRIFIED -- t8. "A TORCH LIGHTING THE WAY TO PROGRESS AND CIVILIZATION" -- t9. THE POOREST REPUBLIC -- tConclusion: A DREAM DEFERRED -- tA Note on Sources -- tNotes -- tBibliography of Primary Sources -- tIndex  aArtemy Kalinovsky's Laboratory of Socialist Development investigates the Soviet effort to make promises of decolonization a reality by looking at the politics and practices of economic development in central Asia between World War II and the collapse of the Soviet Union. Focusing on the Tajik Soviet Socialist Republic, Kalinovsky places the Soviet development of central Asia in a global context.Connecting high politics and intellectual debates with the life histories and experiences of peasants, workers, scholars, and engineers, Laboratory of Socialist Development shows how these men and women negotiated Soviet economic and cultural projects in the decades following Stalin's death. Kalinovsky's book investigates how people experienced new cities, the transformation of rural life, and the building of the world's tallest dam. Kalinovsky connects these local and individual moments to the broader context of the Cold War, shedding new light on how paradigms of development change over time. Throughout the book, he offers comparisons with experiences in countries such as India, Iran, and Afghanistan, and considers the role of intermediaries who went to those countries as part of the Soviet effort to spread its vision of modernity to the postcolonial world.Laboratory of Socialist Development offers a new way to think about the post-war Soviet Union, the relationship between Moscow and its internal periphery, and the interaction between Cold War politics and domestic development. Kalinovsky's innovative research pushes readers to consider the similarities between socialist development and its more familiar capitalist version.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Sep 2018)08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2018z978311066747908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501715587423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501715587.jpg  a978-3-11-060403-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishb2018